comments.text: With abs you need a lot of testing before you get optimal setting, i use a enclosure with open front door, with a pei sheet(a.k.a Ultem), i have a small fan with a shroud going toward the print, the cooling setting makes all the difference between a failed print and a delamination problem. you need to be somewhere between the two... i have modified the Wall part with a bit of a curve instead of a nearly 90° slope, that was the most likely failure point and should be better now. will post a remix..

I was headed out for vacation and wanted a timer for the light on the front of my house. So I made one with stuff I had laying around. 
It is a very simple servo project with an arduino board to control it. The time program I created will turn on the light as soon as you turn it on wait 4 hours and turn the light off for 20 hours. (These are all very approximate the way I did the programming, as I was not after accuracy.) After a 2 week vacation it was off by about an hour, but hey close enough. :)

You'll need to get:
1) Ardunio
2) 9g mini servo (part number ERCS900 I got mine from Hobby-Lobby.com)
3) 3 male to male jumper wires
4) 2 longer switch plate cover screws
5) 2 #6 washers for spacers You'll need to do:

  • Print the Servo mount

  • Attach the servo to the mount using the supplied screws with the servo

  • Attach the long skinny servo bar to the servo.

  • Remove the screws from the light switch cover and mount the assembly over the light switch plate using longer screws. (you can steal longer screws from the outlet covers near by) I also used a couple washers between the mount and the light switch cover for added clearance to make the switch work consistently.

  • Upload the Servo_Switch.pde program to the ardunio.

  • Mount the Ardunio board to the wall near by (I used bright pink thumbtacks)

  • Connect the servo to the ardunio using male jumper wires. Red to 5V, Black to Ground and Orange to pin 9

  • Plug the ardunio in and watch the magic as the light switch is turned on.

  • Be prepared for questions like "You're not going to burn the house down while we are on vacation, are you?"

title: Waterproof ROV Tether control box and reel cable management additions for use with an ROV

description.text:
This is a set of parts to turn a Tecnec Jackreel 4 ( Also known as a Shill GT310 reel in the U.K.) into a full featured ROV tether interface using the Blue robotics Fathom line of tether extenders. It should fit a Fathom S or X board, I have tested it with a fathom X. There are two variants here, a waterproof version with waterproof connectors, and a simpler non waterproof version.

Build thread is here
http://discuss.bluerobotics.com/t/my-tether-spool/884

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 5

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.5mm nozzle

Infill:

85% or better

Notes:

This was printed with ABS, other materials would also work but as a dock or a boat hull can get very warm, i would avoid PLA just due to the melt temperature issue.

To build one of these, you will need a tecnec Jack reel 4 ( I bought this one https://www.bhphotovideo.com/c/product/1008492-REG/hybrid_fiber_systems_jackreel_f4_high_performance_fiber_optic.html )
16 M3 heat set inserts ( https://www.mcmaster.com/#94180a331/=17gvlmb )
a variaty of m3 stainless bolts (should be 12 8mm ones and 4 10mm ones) and 4 12mm M3 botls and nuts for the cable stop. You will also need 4 m3 12mm long bolts and nuts to hold the cable roller and the velcro bit to the jackreel
6 13mm OD 4mm ID stainless steel bearings. (something like this should work https://www.mcmaster.com/#7804k103/=17gvmvh )
2 sections of 16MM OD X 13MM ID (1.5MM WALL) 316 SEAMLESS STAINLESS STEEL TUBE X 200MM cut to 104mm long lengths. (I used these ones because I couldn't find thicker ones locally, but they took forever to get here http://www.ebay.com/itm/322462598200?_trksid=p2060353.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT)
2x 13 mm overall lenght M4 bolts and nuts for the inner bearings and 4x 32mm long M4 bolts and nuts for the rollers
the non waterproof box uses rivets to attach. the waterproof one is designed to use stainless steel plastic screws
You will need 1 RCA to 2 wire vga balun (well technically 2, since you'll want one on the other end as well) You can optionally just fill that hole in instead if you don't wish to use a secondary camera feed
You will also need 4 m3 bolt sized 1/8" plastic spacer standoff things to move the Fathom board away from the brass inserts.
a 50mm section of blue robotics tether http://www.bluerobotics.com/store/cables/fathom-tether-nb-4p-26awg-r1/ or whichever other cable you would like to use. The cable stop and rollers are sized for that cable though.
a 6 or 8 wire slip ring of some sort, I used this one:
http://www.ebay.com/itm/141778020060?_trksid=p2060353.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT
For the waterproof version you will also need RTV or clear silicone
a "NETWORK TECHNOLOGIES case side waterproof rj45 connector with jack N cap " (no idea where to get those, I bought one on Ebay Possibly part numbers RJ45-5EWTP-CS-JCK RJ45-5EWTP-CB and RJ45-5EWTP-CAP (this looks to be the same thing http://www.ebay.com/itm/RJ45-Ethernet-LAN-Network-AP-Plug-Jack-Socket-Connector-8-Core-Waterproof-IP68-/291866258836?hash=item43f495ad94:g:uZwAAOSwFV9Xzo7M)
and a waterproof USB mini cable interface. I actually have another one on the way with the pigtail since I can't find a USB mini male male cable in a short length anywhere. But for now this one worls http://www.ebay.com/itm/220627320201?_trksid=p2060353.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT (that is for powering the Fathom board, you could also run 2 wires to the battery contact using that hole instead.

Everything should print without support.

Assembly:
Insert heat set inserts everywhere that looks like it needs one, using the pictures as guides. Install the bearings in the cable roller sides first, then insert the longer bolts and last 4 bearings for the main rollers. Cut the rollers to length using a tubing cutter, clean up the inside edge to ensure it fits over the bearing, then bolt the assembly togherer. Use the upper frame to locate the holes you need to drill in the jack wheel handle and then bolt that on. repeat that with the velcro cable holder on the other side.

For the box, assuming you are using the waterproof version, use the box held flush against the back of the handle so it isn't obstructing the roller to locate and mark the 3 holes for the plastic screws, and then drill a small pilot hole. Then mount the box using 3 screws

Next, drill a 13mm hole in the inside front center hub cover for the slipring. Drill a similar sized hole on the back side of the frame. Screw the slipring adaptor into the center hub using stianless screws in the recessed pocket, and then screw the slipring over it, making sure the spinny around part is inside the reel. Route the static wires into the back box. Now glue or tape the potting guide curved section to the back frame.

Install the RCA balun in the box and attach to 2 wires. Now fill that compartment with RTV or clear silicon and secure the lid. Install the 3 potting well lids around the screw holes for the box, making sure to use the one with the cable cutout on the bottom, and then fill those 3 sections with RTV or silicon as well. Fill the potting guide curved section as well.

Now, assemble the lid by installing the network cable and mini usb connectors, and run their respective wires to the fathom board. Mount the fathom board using M3 bolts and spacers, and attach two of the tether wires. When everything is ready to be assembled, run a bead of rtv or silicon around the edge of the box in the gasket groove, then bolt the lid down. Allow to dry for the manufacture reccommended duration.

Next attach the tether wire to the slipring through the integral spool hole. fill that hole with silicon. if you have some, add some spare ROV float material into the center drum, then attach the lid with silicon and screws to make it theoretically watertight. There will be a future drill interface (for higher speed tether rolling up) and cable wrap section that goes here, but ignore those for now.

The last remaining thing is to finish your tether interface. I used 8 pin Seaconn connectors and this cable support grip https://www.mcmaster.com/#69675k23/=17gw3j1 along with 3m Scotchcast flexible cable overmold resin to attach the seconn 8 pin micro wetcon section. That allows me to still attach to the kevlar strength member in the ROV cable and tie that directly to structure, but still have a removable tether. There are plenty of other methods as well, so use the connectors and attachments that make sense for you.

I modeled this in free hand by looking at various images and using Google Earth to get a reference.

Here is a recreated "resistor pack" that is common on C3 corvettes original gauges. The original resistance is calibrated at 90 Ohms. With this pack you can modify the resistance to work with the replacement gauge senders that are not 100% accurate.
The OEM Sensor on the engine will read about 80 Ohms when at 212F Replacement sensors read 102 OHMS at 212F.
In my case I am installing an LS1 from an 02 Camaro and needed a factory sensor that would fit in the new style heads (M12 x 1.5) I used this "Thing" to re-calibrate my gauge to a lower ohm 1998 Camaro LS1 coolant sensor which read 170 Ohms at 212*F.
It is now within 3 degrees of the factory gauge.

The same calibration resistors can be found on the backs of the oil pressure gauge, the fuel gauge Use Kanthal wire. For mine I used 32gauge and came up with about 30 Ohms in the board. I was told it is exposed to release any heat build up otherwise a traditional resistor might have worked

I have uploaded the adapter as two separate parts so it can be modified for different size hoses. My ShopVac and hoses are very old, so newer models might have different hose diameters. title: Susan 2.0, a Large Format Reprap i3

description.text:
Susan 2.0 is a large format reprap i3 style printer. It's based on the classic Prusa i3 but features much beefier connection parts to ensure strength and stability for larger frames. The frame itself is made from 3030 aluminum extrusion and can be scaled to make a variety of build volumes. I built mine with 20" extrusions for X & Y, and 24" extrusions for z, giving it a 14x14x16" build volume. The hotend is an E3D-v6 with a mk8 style direct-drive extruder and proximity sensor probe for finding Z and mesh leveling the build platform. The bed is topped with a PEI sheet to help part adhesion. A separate high-voltage silicone heater and controller are used to heat the bed. The printer is controlled using a Rambo 1.3 Mini running Marlin. All the motion components run on 10mm chromed linear shafts to ensure accuracy and durability. Each component is fixed to the frame using M4 slide nuts and M4 12mm screws.

I am currently building a second Susan 2.0 and will be photographing the entire assembly process to make a guide on how to assemble this printer. However, anyone who has built a printer before could surely figure out the assembly steps just from the part files and pictures.

title: Enhanced Magazine for Blaster for 13.5mm Darts

description.text: When I first printed the magazine, I felt that 6 darts just isnt enough, am average Nerf gun holds at least 11 in one magazine, AND is able to feed in any orientation. Which prompted me to take the dimensions of the original and build it up from the ground to create a rubber band advanced magazine which holds over double the original amount+1 dart if you are lucky. Thus with this Magazine it puts you above par when it comes to capacity compared to other Nerf guns.

When both parts are completed, insert the push block into the magazine with the curve facing down.

Insert a cut piece of drinking straw into the hole in the push block(keeps the rubber band from breaking)

String rubber band through the straw. you dont need much power to advance darts so I used a long thin rubber band.

you can add a little bit of a lubricant to it to allow it to slider easier, but I would recommend a dry lubricant or just a little bit of vegetable oil on the block part.

Got the required dimensions from the original magazine such as the spacing of the clips, and the slot width. Took that info and drew up a design in Autodesk Inventor, the first design was lacking as it didn't have the crossbar at the top, so I iterated that. description.text:
The 20mm x 20mm x 210mm rectangular tube was modelled to test out my PrintrBot Simple V2 after a custom mod to expand the Z axis.  
A shorter version, the 20mm x 20mm x 10mm with 2mm walls, is used to test/calibrate the X, Y, and Z axis.  
The 182mm tower test printing a narrow tower(solid).

Just download the STL files and slice them in your slicer of choice with your desired settings, then print. The axis calibration can be done by the following: Get your current steps per mm for a given axis. Measure the printed output from the 20x20x10 object for the given axis. Apply the following formula: ( original steps per mm * 20 ) / ( measured dimension ) The result is your new steps per mm that you should use for that axis. Repeat for each axis. An example: You query your printer with the following GCODE: M501 On the PrintrBoard, this will return various values, including the steps per mm for each axis: Steps per unit: M92 X84.40 Y84.40 Z2525.00 E96.00 Let's say for your given printer, you have 84.40 steps per mm for your X axis. You print out the 20mm x 20mm x 10mm target. When you measure the X dimension of the object, you find that the measurement is 20.80mm. ( 84.40 * 20 ) / 20.80 = 81.15384 So, you enter this new value to be saved to the EEPROM on your PrintrBoard: M92 X81.15384 M500 To confirm: M501

description.text:
This replaces the Anet A8's extruder lock with one that is a bit more comfortable to use, than pushing on a screw. It is, for the most part, modelled after the original, but with a few changes. The internal mechanics are the same, however; the filament hole has a gradual narrowing rather than the step in the original, the spring is held in place by geometry, and there is a push knob which threads into the main block in place of a screw.

My intent was to re-purpose the nut from the original push screw to hold the bearing in place. As it turned out, this was not required, as the hole diameter ended up such that it caught the threads of the screw, and holds the bearing in place perfectly. That, and the screw was too short to reach the nut anyway. If your threads don't catch as did mine, you may need to get a slightly longer screw to catch the threads on the nut.

description.text:
The Royal Game Of Ur is one of the oldest games to be discovered. Predated only by the Egyptian game of Senet, the board found in 1920 is estimated to be about 5000 years old.
Ever since I found out about the existence of the game (3 days ago), I wanted to play it but unfortunately I couldn't find any vendor who sells it so I decided to make my own.

!Beware that I haven't yet printed it since I just finished designing it!

UPDATE
-I have added a new version of the board with smaller depth for the impressions (1mm) this should drastically cut the printing time while still giving you a nice piece overall.
-Tried printing the impressions and my Anet A8 managed to print them well at 0.2mm resolution.
-I have also made another version with a small drawer inside of it which will fit the dice and the pawns.
Print this version with light supports and then take them out at the end. This version has not yet been tested by me

You will need to print 4 tetrahedron dice (I recommend 100% infill for good balance) and mark two vertices on each of the four tetrahedral so when you trow the 4 dice, you will get a number from 0 to 4.

You will also need to print several pawns and preferably paint half of them black or print them in black filament. But you don't have to limit yourself to just black and white, any other color combinations can work just as good.

Print the two board parts then fit them together. Depending on your printer, the fit will be good or bad; if the fit is too lose, put some glue in, if it's to tight, sand it down a bit.
You can learn how to play the game from this video made by The British Museum:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WZskjLq040I

This is a work in progress since I still have to test the print so stay tuned!

description.text:
608 bearings are really cheap by bearing standards. For instance, you can get a pack of 30 608ZZ bearings on ebay for only $15 shipped (from China, of course). That's only $0.50 per bearing!
The spool holders I've seen so far either don't have a foot I like, don't use the type of rod I want, or don't use the size of bearing I have on hand. This thing fixes these things for me and if it does so for you, too, great!
I've included the OpenSCAD source and the compiled STL file.

You're going to need 4 x 8 mm or 5/16 in. threaded rods of lengths useful for your spool. You're also going to need 4 608 bearings. Use 8 mm or 5/16 in. nuts (depending on which threaded rod you used) to secure enerything.

This exercise was part of my continuing effort to climb the learning curve for CAD & 3D printing.

The screw itself is pretty much sorted. Apparently the eight-vane configuration is somewhat optimal. (Found a paper on the subject.)

Note the design (in Onshape) is parameterized (partly) and properly(?) constrained. You might want to keep the size of the screw small (by changing the "length" parameter) when doing test prints, to save print time. You could make a larger screw (by changing the "length" and "case" parameters) and the rest of the parts should adjust properly.

The top end of the screw can be turned by the hand crank. Alternatively, you could remove the crank and turn the screw with an 8mm Allen key - perhaps attached to an electric motor or drill.

These are the pieces for the boardgame I've published at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:229954. They are 17mm (0.6") tall - Pretty small. They were created with Designspark by drawing the outline in 2D mode, pulling it to 10mm then rounding the edges. They are a single colour print in PLA. The coloured eyes are 1.75mm filament fed through the eye holes.

Print several of these at once - I was doing them in batches of 6.
I made the eye-holes slightly larger than the 1.75mm filament but found that some gave a good fit and some were slightly too small, depending on the filament I was printing with.
If you don't have a 1.75mm drill, I found the ideal tool to correct the hole size was a pair of compasses of the type pictured : Retract the pointy bit and set the compasses to minimum radius. The thread will screw into the undersize holes and cut a thread as it goes. Keep screwing once the piece meets the knurled nut to strip the thread, then a couple of dozen turns more. Unscrew and the filament will be a slightly loose fit through the hole. Glue the filament in using thin cyanoacrylate adhesive and use a pair of flat-edged cutters to cut off flush.

This is all in good fun, thought it would be funny to model the Fry fork from McDonalds recent ad campaign and make a joke out of the whole thing

To use this stick 3 fries inside the top container area and dip them into your sauce

This is a simplistic model and doesn't take long to print, If you do choose to print this i recommend you use supports on the inner fry containment area. Please use food safe plastics and DO NOT use toxic plastics since this will be used with food.

Hope you find this funny like i did. Maybe my jokes are just silly and cheesy

Step 1 | Become notably bored.

To begin this wondrous project i was browsing youtube and came across the Frork video from McDonalds, that gave me an idea and i cant just turn on the idea of creating something just for a joke!

I was thinking about the design and realized the first step would be to get the length and width of a french fry from mcdonald's. So instead of going out at first I used the trusty google. I stumbled on this MIT paper about the average length of a french fry but yet, no width. I had to go to McDonalds and purchase a small fry for myself to measure. Turns out the average length of a McDonald's french fry is 6.86mm.

Step 2 | ???

Went to modeling this on Fusion 360. Once i came up with the base design i printed 3 versions with minor changes here and there, and did the extensive testing of dipping it in sauce to seeing if it can hold it in the chamber well.

Step 3 | Design and Publish

Once i got everything done with the model i went to design the silly graphics, This is all out of parody and as a funny joke the designs are supposed to look like this is a revolutionary technology to brace the world but obviously its a fork to hold fries for dipping in sauce. The font im using is Proxima Nova.

Well, I hope you find this slightly funny or get a slight smirk at least.

description.text:
Here are some circular forms in two lengths that can be used to make necklaces and bracelets. They can be printed in different colors and joined together with connectors. The connecting pieces are half circles which snap together. The pictured necklace is approximately a foot in diameter.

Two non adjustable bracelets are also provided - one small - one large. The smaller bracelet fits easily around a 2 inch cylinder; the larger one fits a 3 inch cylinder.

The connectors do not need support. An extra shell makes the pieces sturdier and the support easier to remove. All the pieces had a bit removed from their bases to aid adhesion to the build platform.

description.text:
Remix of Anet A8 Mainboard Electronics case. I expanded, offset main board and changed venting design. Also added wire retainers on inside to help hold wires in place.

With the mainboard offset you will need new screws to mount the main board and mosfet. I have the inserts designed for this screw.

The case will fasten to the Anet A8 frame with M3 bolt and nut. I used this fan and mounted it with M3 bolt and nut.

I ordered this kit of bolts, nuts and washers to have around as spares.
